President Barack Obama has proclaimed April 21 to April 29, 2012, as National Park Week in the United States. In his proclamation, he highlights the importance of preserving and protecting the country's national heritage for future generations. President Obama mentions the efforts made by President Theodore Roosevelt over a century ago to establish national parks, monuments, bird reservations, and forests. He also discusses his own administration's commitment to conservation, including setting aside over 2 million acres of federal wilderness and establishing national monuments. The President emphasizes the role of national parks in promoting outdoor recreation, boosting rural economies, and increasing tourism. As part of the National Park Week celebrations, all 397 national parks will offer free admission during this period. President Obama encourages all Americans to visit their national parks and appreciate the unique blessings they offer as a nation.